-Introduction: question: Among population with known race category, Whats the proportion of each race affected by the covid-19 across the U.S? which race was being affected most? (at each state, which race have the highest number positive cases and death cases? )

data background: the primary data source is the COVID Racial Data Tracker.They collect, cross-check, and publish COVID-19 data from 56 US states and territories in three main areas: testing, patient outcomes, and, via The COVID Racial Data Tracker, racial and ethnic demographic information. Data is being updated twice per week.

-Methods: Given the data being provied, we consider removing the NAs. We sum up the case number of each race by the latest updated numbers, then summarized the proportion of races and ethnicity for both cases and deaths number across the States. The software would be R. #look at the data

#making a pie chart for race compnent

slices = pct_case
lbls = cases_name
pct <- round(slices/sum(slices)*100)
lbls <- paste(lbls, pct) # add percents to labels
lbls <- paste(lbls,"%",sep="") # ad % to labels
pie(slices,labels = lbls, col=rainbow(length(lbls)),
   main="Pie Chart of Cases")

slices = pct_death
lbls = deaths_name
pct <- round(slices/sum(slices)*100)
lbls <- paste(lbls, pct) # add percents to labels
lbls <- paste(lbls,"%",sep="") # ad % to labels
pie(slices,labels = lbls, col=rainbow(length(lbls)),
   main="Pie Chart of Deaths")

4.conclusion Overall, among positive cases with known races, white, LatinX, and Black are the three most affected races; these three races also have the highest death number among known races death.
